				<p><p>This should be straightforward, because the throttle can never provide negative acceleration and the brake can never provide positive acceleration.  </p>

<p>It sounds like you want to create a linear mapping from an input acceleration $(a)$ to a throttle and brake output.  If the response of the throttle system for a given velocity $v$ is </p>

<p>$$
f(x_{throttle}) = a
$$ </p>

<p>(where $a &gt; 0$), and the response of the braking system is </p>

<p>$$
g(y_{brake}) = a
$$ </p>

<p>(where ($a &lt; 0$ if $v &gt; 0$ and is 0 otherwise), you will just define the controller in a piecewise fashion.</p>

<p>$$
control_{throttle}(a) = \begin{cases} f^{-1}(a) &amp; a \gt 0 \\ 0 &amp; a \le 0 \end{cases}
$$
and
$$
control_{brake}(a) = \begin{cases}g^{-1}(a) &amp; a \lt 0 \\ 0 &amp; a &gt; 0  \\ C_{parkingbrake} &amp; a = 0 \end{cases}
$$</p>
</p><br>
